{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"35965554-0c0b-4e4d-9728-ec1091f61ba9","content":"The current working directory is empty, so there's no project-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance:\n\n---\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump` (NativeAOT)**\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump` (it's a CoreCLR tool). On macOS, use the OS-level crash reporting instead:\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps via `ulimit`** before running your app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   /path/to/your-app\n   ```\n   Core files are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **If `/cores` is missing or empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking it and the directory exists with correct permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your-app -c /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\n5. **For .NET-specific managed state**, load the SOS debugging extension in lldb if available:\n   ```\n   (lldb) plugin load libsosplugin.dylib\n   ```\n   Note: SOS support for NativeAOT dumps is limited compared to CoreCLR.\n\n**Key takeaway:** On macOS, rely on `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/` for full core dumps, and `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for Apple's automatic crash reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e3c4c88-12eb-4c6b-b39c-1d2e09dbcd39","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"6817:1E23:579E0B:657EE2:69FD4238"},"id":"d9e5110c-b685-4b7f-b704-fa8b5c9485f1","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:54:11.651Z","parentId":"460be617-bf78-477c-9918-cca56195c5de"}
